" }}}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 31 "1.  Graphing functions and the " }
{TEXT 257 4 "plot" }{TEXT -1 89 " command.  The Maple command for plot
ting the graph of an explicitly defined function is:" }}{PARA 0 "" 0 "
" {TEXT -1 5 "     " }{TEXT 258 0 "" }{TEXT 259 4 "plot" }{TEXT 260 0 
"" }{TEXT -1 2 "( " }{TEXT 261 4 "expr" }{TEXT -1 2 ", " }{TEXT 266 1 
"x" }{TEXT -1 20 "=range [, options]);" }}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 6 "
where " }{TEXT 262 4 "expr" }{TEXT 267 1 " " }{TEXT -1 24 "is a symbol
ic expression" }{TEXT 264 1 " " }{TEXT -1 48 "which represents the fun
ction to be plotted and " }{TEXT 263 1 "x" }{TEXT -1 38 " is the indep
endent variable used in  " }{TEXT 265 4 "expr" }{TEXT -1 25 "  to defi
ne the function." }}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 81 "Several options exist
 to change way the plot will appear.  These options include:" }}{PARA 
0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 0 "" }}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 126 "            y=
range                       this allows the user to specifiy the range
 of output values which Maple will display" }}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT 
-1 113 "            thickness=value           this controls the thickn
ess of the plotted curve.  value = 1, 2, 3, 4, or 5" }}{PARA 0 "" 0 "
" {TEXT -1 119 "            color=value                 this sets the \+
color of the plotted curve.  value = red, green, blue, cyan, etc." }}
{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 0 "" }}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 160 "For each
 of the following functions provide a plot to represent the graph the \+
function.  Choose a range that will optimally represent the features o
f the graph." }}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 0 "" }}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT 
-1 16 "a.    y = 3x - 1" }}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 0 "" }}{EXCHG 
