}}{EXCHG {PARA 0 "> " 0 "" {MPLTEXT 1 0 0 "" }}}{EXCHG {PARA 0 "> " 0 
"" {MPLTEXT 1 0 0 "" }}}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 229 "2.  Polynomials:
  Intercepts and Sign.  There are several features about the graphs of
 polynomials which are important to track.  These features inform us a
bout the behavior of the function.  Those features include the followi
ng:" }}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 0 "" }}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 57 "  \+
  a.    x-intercepts of the function                   " }}{PARA 0 "" 
0 "" {TEXT -1 129 "                       Those values where the graph
 crosses the x-axis.  Those points are solutions of the equation y = f
(x) = 0." }}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 105 "    b.    regions (intervals
) in the domain of the function where the values of the function are p
ositive" }{TEXT 311 34 "(the x values where y is positive)" }}{PARA 0 
"" 0 "" {TEXT -1 215 "                       Those regions where the g
raph lies above the x-axis.  For a continuous function, and in particu
lar for polynomials, these regions are bounded by the intercepts and m
ay stretch to +/- infinity." }}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 106 "    c.   \+
 regions (intervals) in the domain of the function where the values of
 the function are negative " }{TEXT 312 34 "(the x values where y is n
egative)" }}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 215 "                       Those
 regions where the graph lies below the x-axis.  For a continuous func
tion, and in particular for polynomials, these regions are bounded by \+
the intercepts and may stretch to +/- infinity." }}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" 
{TEXT -1 36 "    d.   y-intercept of the function" }}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" 
{TEXT -1 107 "                       The value where the graph crosses
 the y-axis.  The value of the function when x = 0." }}{PARA 0 "" 0 "
" {TEXT -1 20 "    e.   end limits " }{TEXT 313 10 "(y values)" }}
{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 384 "                       For a polynomial,
 its values will become either arbitrarily large in a positive sense o
r arbitrarily large in a negative sense as the domain values tend to i
nfinity.  Graphically, the values on the graph will growth arbitrarily
 large positively (go up off the graph) or arbitrarily large negative \+
(go down off the graph) as the domain values tend to infinity.  " }}
{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 87 "                       Similar behavior h
olds true for approaches to negative infinity." }}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" 
{TEXT -1 0 "" }}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 150 "For each of the followin
g polynomials,  provide a graph of the polynomial.  Choose a range tha
t will optimally represent the features of the graph.   " }{TEXT 268 
4 "Also" }{TEXT -1 90 ", for each polynomial find each of the above fi
ve graphcial characteristics (a.  thru e.):" }}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT 
-1 0 "" }}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 5 "a.   " }{XPPEDIT 18 0 "y = 6*x^2
+24*x-8" "6#/%\"yG,(*&\"\"'\"\"\"*$%\"xG\"\"#F(F(*&\"#CF(F*F(F(\"\")!
\"\"" }}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 0 "" }}{EXCHG {PARA 0 "> " 0 "" 
{MPLTEXT 1 0 17 "r1:=6*x^2+24*x-8;" }}{PARA 11 "" 1 "" {XPPMATH 20 "6#
>%#r1G,(*&\"\"'\"\"\")%\"xG\"\"#F(F(*&\"#CF(F*F(F(\"\")!\"\"" }}}
