ues of the function are positive are from (-infinity,2)and from (4, +i
nfinity)" }}{PARA 258 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 102 "The regions in the domain \+
of the function where the values of the function are negative are from
 (2,4)" }}{PARA 258 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 80 "The endpoints of the function
 are +infinity for both the left and right regions." }}}{EXCHG {PARA 
0 "> " 0 "" {MPLTEXT 1 0 0 "" }}}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 0 "" }}
{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 841 "3.  Polynomials:  Local extreme values a
nd monotonicity.  Beyond information of the type gathered above about \+
intercepts and signs of a polynomial,  other important information can
 be determined from the so called \"critical points\" of a polynomial.
  The critical points of a polynomial are the intercepts of its deriva
tive.  Since the derivative of a function at a point represents the sl
ope of the tangent line to the graph of the that function at the point
, then the intercepts of the derivative are places where the the tange
nt lines to the function are flat, i.e., are horizontal lines.  At suc
h places the graph is neither increasing nor decreasing.  Elsewhere th
e graph must be either increasing or decreasing.  For a polynomial, lo
cal extreme values (local maximums or local minimums) must occur at th
e intercepts of the derivative.  " }}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 0 "" }}
{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 80 "     The follwing features are important \+
in analyzing the graph of a polynomial:" }}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 0 
"" }}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 41 "     f.   critical points of the fun
ction" }}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 99 "                      For a poly
nomial these are the intercepts of the derivative of the polynomial" }
}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 67 "     g.    local maximum points of the g
raph of a function y = f(x)" }}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 274 "         \+
             These are points (x,y) on the graph of the function for w
hich the y-value is locally the largest value of the function.  Nearby
 values on the graph are lower.  For a polynomials the x-value of the \+
point (x,y) must be a critical point of the polynomial." }}{PARA 0 "" 
0 "" {TEXT -1 67 "     h.   local minimum points of the graph of a fun
ction y = f(x) " }}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 276 "                     \+
 These are points (x,y) on the graph of the function for which the y-v
alue is locally the smallest value of the function.  Nearby values on \+
the graph are higher.  For a polynomials the x-value of the point (x,y
) must be a critical point of the polynomial." }}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" 
{TEXT -1 109 "     i.    regions (intervals) in the domain of the func
tion where the values of the function are increasing " }{TEXT 314 27 "
(slope increasing x values)" }}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 249 "         \+
              Those regions where the graph rises as the graph is trav
ersed from left to right.  For a continuous function, and in particula
r for polynomials, these regions are bounded by the critical points an
d may stretch to +/- infinity." }}{PARA 257 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 109 "    \+
 j.    regions (intervals) in the domain of the function where the val
ues of the function are decreasing(" }{TEXT 315 28 "slope decreasing -
